<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="http://talkirish.com/utility/FeedStylesheets/rss.xsl" media="screen"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:slash="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/slash/" xmlns:wfw="http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/"><channel><title>The Irish Language - Grammar, Pronunciation, Games, Myths, Poetry and more</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/40.aspx</link><description>A great place to discuss Irish grammar, pronunciation, and vocabulary.  You'll also find lots of help and information on Irish translations, Irish myths and legends, and Irish poetry. And here's where we have some Irish word games and lots of useful tips on language learning.</description><dc:language>en</dc:language><generator>CommunityServer 2008 SP1 (Build: 30619.63)</generator><item><title>Re: For Ever and Ever (Amen)</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/9777.aspx</link><pubDate>Thu, 06 Mar 2014 20:33:51 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:9777</guid><dc:creator>seano</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><comments>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/9777.aspx</comments><wfw:commentRss>http://talkirish.com/forums/commentrss.aspx?SectionID=40&amp;PostID=9777</wfw:commentRss><description>&lt;p&gt;Whoops! I have to hold up my hands here and say that I got my piece wrong there. It is, as Annalivia says, Tr&amp;iacute; shaol na saol or (le) saol na saol. In my defence, I would just say that being a total heathen prayers have no place in my life in English, Irish, Spanish or any other language, but even so I should have known that. Memory is fickle on the wrong side of fifty Still, being wrong is reputed to be good for the soul ... Profound apologies to all concerned. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;N&amp;iacute; bh&amp;iacute;onn saoi gan locht, agus n&amp;iacute; bh&amp;iacute;onn an daoi gan a chuid lochtanna ach an oiread ...&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item><item><title>Re: For Ever and Ever (Amen)</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/9695.aspx</link><pubDate>Mon, 24 Feb 2014 22:45:33 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:9695</guid><dc:creator>Annalivia</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><comments>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/9695.aspx</comments><wfw:commentRss>http://talkirish.com/forums/commentrss.aspx?SectionID=40&amp;PostID=9695</wfw:commentRss><description>&lt;h1 class="bold_dark"&gt;The Our father ends with &amp;#39;for ever and ever&amp;#39;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h1 class="bold_dark"&gt;The Lord&amp;#39;s Prayer&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;h2&gt;&lt;span class="small_header_dark"&gt;(traditional)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="credit_white_centre"&gt;Our Father, which art in heaven,&lt;br /&gt;
            Hallowed be thy   Name.&lt;br /&gt;
            Thy Kingdom come. &lt;br /&gt;
            Thy will be done in earth, &lt;br /&gt;
            As it is in   heaven.&lt;br /&gt;
            Give us this day our daily bread.&lt;br /&gt;
            And forgive us our   trespasses,&lt;br /&gt;
            As we forgive them that trespass against us. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="credit_white_centre"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
            And lead us not   into temptation, &lt;br /&gt;
            But deliver us from evil. &lt;br /&gt;
        For thine is the kingdom, &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="credit_white_centre"&gt;The   power, and the glory, &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="credit_white_centre"&gt;For ever and ever. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class="credit_white_centre"&gt;Amen.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div style="overflow:hidden;color:#000000;background-color:#ffffff;text-align:left;text-decoration:none;border:medium none;"&gt;
&lt;table id="prayer" align="center"&gt;

&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td id="title"&gt;&amp;Aacute;r nAthair&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td id="text"&gt;
&amp;Aacute;r nAthair, at&amp;aacute; ar neamh: go naofar d&amp;#39;ainm.&lt;br /&gt;
Go dtaga do r&amp;iacute;ocht.&lt;br /&gt;
Go nd&amp;eacute;antar do thoil ar talamh&lt;br /&gt;
mar a dh&amp;eacute;antar ar neamh.&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;Aacute;r n-ar&amp;aacute;n laeth&amp;uacute;il tabhair d&amp;uacute;inn inniu,&lt;br /&gt;
agus maith d&amp;uacute;inn &amp;aacute;r bhfiacha,&lt;br /&gt;
mar a mhaithimid d&amp;aacute;r bhf&amp;eacute;ichi&amp;uacute;naithe f&amp;eacute;in.&lt;br /&gt;
Agus n&amp;aacute; lig sinn i gcath&amp;uacute;,&lt;br /&gt;
ach saor sinn &amp;oacute; olc.&lt;br /&gt;
[&amp;Oacute;ir is leatsa an R&amp;iacute;ocht agus an Chumhacht&lt;br /&gt;
agus an Ghl&amp;oacute;ir, tr&amp;iacute; shaol na saol.]
   &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td id="amen"&gt;&amp;Aacute;im&amp;eacute;an&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;

&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item><item><title>For Ever and Ever (Amen)</title><link>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/9689.aspx</link><pubDate>Fri, 21 Feb 2014 17:14:33 GMT</pubDate><guid isPermaLink="false">0644754f-ff87-49dd-b5e3-0e104f790f4a:9689</guid><dc:creator>seano</dc:creator><slash:comments>0</slash:comments><comments>http://talkirish.com/forums/thread/9689.aspx</comments><wfw:commentRss>http://talkirish.com/forums/commentrss.aspx?SectionID=40&amp;PostID=9689</wfw:commentRss><description>&lt;p&gt;Hi, We have had an enquiry from a lady in England whose grandmother was raised in Wicklow. They used to say a prayer each night, ending with the phrase &amp;#39;for ever and ever&amp;#39;, so this lady would like to find out how to write this phrase and how to pronounce it. There are several ways of saying it, the most common being &amp;oacute; shaol go saol (&amp;aacute;im&amp;eacute;an). The word saol is one of those strange hard-to-translate expressions which has no exact equivalent in English. It means something like life or world and is ultimately derived from the Etruscan language, which gave the Latin language the word saeculum. This was then transformed into saoghal and thence saol in Modern Irish. The phrase &amp;quot;&amp;oacute; shaol go saol&amp;quot; means something like &amp;quot;from world to world&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;from life to life&amp;quot; or &amp;quot;from age to age&amp;quot;. It is pronounced roughly as &amp;quot;oh heal go seal.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Amen is pretty much the same in all languages - in Irish it&amp;#39;s spelled &amp;aacute;im&amp;eacute;an. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hope we aren&amp;#39;t too late with this and a big Breithl&amp;aacute; sona to your grandmother! :-)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;div style="clear:both;"&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>